{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110301/0546.xml":{"full_text":"TOURING EXPERTS\nHOLD CONVENTION\nBetter Facilities for Motor\nists Here and Abroad\nWill Be Sought.\nWays and means of improving the\ntravel services offered America's vast\n\u2022rmy of tourists will receive the atten\ntion of members of the Advisory Com\nmittee of the National Touring Board\nof the American Automobile Associa\ntion, at its annual meeting, which\nopened today at the Willard Hotel.\nTravel experts from all parts of the\nUnited States are gathered for a two\nday study of problems affecting tour\ning in this country, Canada and Mexico.\nThey will go to New York Tuesday\nnight for sessions on Wednesday to\ndelve into questions related to tour\ning abroad, w ith special attention to ex\npediting the travel of thousands of\nmotorists who annually ship their cars\nto foreign countries for touring under\ntheir own power.\nStandardization of facilities for the\nmotoring millions, as well as those who\ntravel by air and water, is the ob\njective of the annual meeting. Among\nthe keynote topie for the sessions here j\nwill be improvement in the millions of\nmaps and touring publications issued\nannually, designation of new routes to\npoints of historical and scenic in\nterest. and other problems vitally as- j\nfecting the tourist.\nW. O. Bryant of Detroit, chairman\nof the A. A. A. National Touring\nBoard, who will preside at the con\nference, is optimistic over the travel\noutlook in the face of the business\ndepression.\n\u201cWhile it cannot be estimated just\nhow much travel has been affected by\nbusiness conditions until reports from\n\u2022very section of the country are con\nsidered,\u201d said Mr. Bryant, \u201cit is ap\nparent that travel has not been\nseriously affected up to the present.\u201d\nNational headquarters of the A. A. A.\nIs represented by Ernest N. Smith, ex\necutive vice president: Charles P.\nClark, general manager: Elmer Jenkins,\nmanager of the National Touring\nBureau, and others.\nThe well known painting by Sir John\nLavery of the sitting of the first So\ncialist government in the House of\nCommons has been given to the City\nof Glasgow.\nWoodward Lothrop\nDown Stairs Store\nSemi-Service and Chiffon Silk Hose\nA Limited Number\u2014Greatly Reduced /J f\nFrom Our Regular Stock to OOC\nChiffon with lisle-lined hems and plaited soles or semi-service silk hose\nwith lisle hems and soles numbers that have sold in great quantities\nat higher prices\u2014oii sale tomorrow at 65c pair. Smart Fall shades. Sizes\nS l 2 to 10.\nTHE DOWN STAIRS STORE\nf\nf Shades Are the High Lights\nBrighten the 1930 Mode in\nses\u2019 New Dresses\nAs a pleasing contrast to her dark I\ncoat, the fashion-wise miss chooses\nbrightly colored frocks and in\ncombinations of these same high\nshades. This low-priced collection I\nfeatures lovely \"bright shades of\u2014 I\nGreen Brass I\nWine Sand 1\nvery smartly trimmed with lace, I\nbuttons, embroidery and fur cloth. M\nCantons, chiffons, jerseys and novelty M\nwoollens also a few very new\nj prints as well as black and brown.\nJ 1 THE DOWN STAIRS STORE\nNew Styles\u2014Very Low Priced \u2014in\nRayon Pajamas, 5|.95\nOs fine quality rayon with very wide\ntrousers, these attractive pajamas come in\na wide choice of styles (only one of them\nsketched), with or without sleeves and\nwith smart new necklines. In lovely color S'\nOne-piece Pajamas with cowl neck-\nRussian style Pajamas with long jjPRI ___\nsleeves $3.95 X/y\nARRANGE SORORITY DANCE PROGRAM\ni\n\nThe Phi Sigma Epsilon Sorority members plan to hold a dance at the\nShoreham Hotel on Friday. Members of the committee in charge are, left to\nright, front row: Louise Warfield, Alice Locraft and Jane Carr. Back row: Helen\nFader, Peggy Batcheller, chairman, and Barbara Shannon. \u2014Star Staff Photo.\nLAWN MOWER WON\nCitizens' Association Decides Kaliv\nj eretenos Property Is Best Kept.\nJohn Kaliveretenos of 1341 Gerard\nstreet will be awarded the grand prize\nof a lawn mower for having the best\nkept lawn in Columbia Heights at the\nmeeting of the Citizens\u2019 Association\nTuesday night, at 1435 Park road.\nOthers to be given certificates are\nJohn T. Sterling, 1200 Euclid street;\nMrs. Mary E. Myers, 3011 Thirteenth\nstreet; Colin H. Livingstone, 1249 Ken\nyon street; George T. Hutchison, 3620\nTenth street, and S. E. Reed, 1314 Ran\ndolph street.\nThe Quakers have always admitted;\nwomen to the ministry\u2019.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., MONDAY, NOVEMBER 3. 1930.\nSURVEY WELFARE WORK\nWashington Family Agencies Be\ning Studied by Experts.\nFrancis H. McLean of the Family\nWelfare Association of America is mak\ning a survey of all the family welfare\nagencies in Washington, the Council\nof Social Agencies announced today.\nIt is hoped the survey will furnish a\nbasis for community planning and in\ncrease efficiency in the family welfare\nfield through a disclosure of needs not\nnow covered.\nMr. McLean is being assisted in the\ni work by Mrs. Roy Huff, formerly with\nthe St. LouLs Provident Association,\n1 and Miss Miriam McCaffrey, who for\nfive years was with the Family Welfare\nAssociation of Wisconsin.\nBy DAY By NIGHT\nThe line-up is a sporty one\u2014selected The sideline sparkles \u2014formal ele\nbecause of their youthful swagger and gance at last reigns at the greatest of\neminent suitability for the rigors of an American sports \u2014for after the game\nafternoon in the stadium. there\u2019s celebrating to do.\nI\nFASHION SHOPS, SECOND FLOOR\nLANSBURGH'S\nToy Departments\nRegister Either 7th Bth and E Sts.\u2014NAtio\u00bb\u00abl 9800\nPlace for Lessons\nNo Connection with Any Other Washington Store\n\nB-3","height":"25482","width":"19899"}}
